It has papered over centuries of racially motivated cruelty and exploitation—sources of the structural oppression experienced today by its Black and indigenous population. Linking the country’s violent past to its dire present, Schwarcz shows why the social democratic left was defeated and how Jair Bolsonaro ascended to the presidency.Schwarcz travels through five hundred years of colonial history to consider Brazil’s allegiance to slavery, which made it the last country to abolish the system. She delves into eight elements that pervade Brazil’s problematic culture: racism, bossism, patrimonialism, corruption, inequality, violence, gender issues, and intolerance. But Schwarcz also argues that Brazil’s future is not absolutely hopeless. History is not destiny, and even as the nation experiences its worst crises ever—social, political, moral, and environmental—it has the potential to overcome them.A stark, revealing investigation into Brazil’s difficult roots, Brazilian Authoritarianism shines a light on how the country might imagine a more hopeful path forward.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthoritarianismzBrazilxHistory. 0aAuthoritarianismzBrazil. 0aRacismzBrazilxHistory. 0aSocial problemszBrazil. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Fascism & Totalitarianism.2bisacsh  aAdolescence.  aAgribusiness.  aAmendment.  aAnachronism.  aAnthropologist.  aAristocracy.  aAttempt.  aAuthoritarianism.  aBlack people.  aBoundary marker.  aBrazilians.  aCess.  aCitizenship.  aCivil service.  aClientelism.  aClothing.  aColonialism.  aColonization.  aCommunity leader.  aCorruption.  aCriminalization.  aCruelty.  aDemocracy.  aDictatorship.  aDilma Rousseff.  aDissemination.  aDrug cartel.  aEconomic inequality.  aEquality and diversity (United Kingdom).